rankine.journal.cat_mechanics.finite_wat: A config enabled by default, which makes water slightly less renewable. Infinite water sources can only be created below the local water table height. A mechanical way of bringing water to the surface is described in the latter pages.
The Dowsing Rod is used to detect the local water height. Right clicking the ground will display a message above the hotbar.

The Ground Tap will generate a source block of water when connected to an appropriate pipe network. That network consists of a Flood Gate placed below the water table height and connected through Metal Pipes. Multiple taps can be on the same pipe line.
rankine.journal.cat_mechanics.name: Mechanics
rankine.journal.cat_mechanics.sluicing.t: Sluicing is a general term for the act of sifting through material under a stream of water. Components can be separated from parent material in a more manual way too.

rankine.journal.cat_sediments.desc: Dirt is too simple of a term to describe the complex matrix of organic material and pulverized rocks. A better term is soil, but there are more small particles than just that.

rankine.journal.cat_mechanics.finite_wat: A config enabled by default, which makes water slightly less renewable. Infinite water sources can only be created below the local water table height. A mechanical way of bringing water to the surface is described in the latter pages.
The Dowsing Rod is used to detect the local water height. Right clicking the ground will display a message above the hotbar.

The Ground Tap will generate a source block of water when connected to an appropriate pipe network. That network consists of a Flood Gate placed below the water table height and connected through Metal Pipes. Multiple taps can be on the same pipe line.

rankine.journal.cat_mechanics.sluicing.t: Sluicing is a general term for the act of sifting through material under a stream of water. Components can be separated from parent material in a more manual way too.
